Exploring data from the GESIS German General Social Survey - ALLBUS 2021

R User

2022-08-19

#Data Wrangling

library(tidyverse)
library(naniar)
library(sjlabelled)
library(haven)

inverter <- function (var) {
  max(var, na.rm = TRUE) - var + 1
}

allbus_2021 <- read_sav("../data/allbus_2021/ZA5280_v1-0-0.sav") %>% 
  remove_all_labels()

allbus_2021_subset  <- allbus_2021  %>% 
  select(respid,
         sex,
         agec,
         educ,
         left_right = pa01,
         party_vote = pv01,
         sat_dem = ps03,
         xeno1 = ma01b,
         xeno2 = ma02,
         xeno3 = ma03,
         xeno4 = ma04,
         contact1 = mc01,
         contact2 = mc02,
         contact3 = mc03,
         contact4 = mc04,
         trust_gov = pt12,
         life_satf = ls01
  ) %>% 
  replace_with_na_all(condition = ~.x < 0)  %>% 
  mutate(sex = recode_factor(sex,
                             `1`= "Male",
                             `2` = "Female",
                             `3` = "Non-binary"),
         sat_dem = recode(sat_dem,
                          `1` = 6,
                          `2` = 5,
                          `3` = 4,
                          `4` = 3,
                          `5` = 3,
                          `6`= 1),
         agec = recode_factor(agec,
                              `1`= "<= 25 years",
                              `2`= "26 to 30 years",
                              `3` = "31 to 35 years",
                              `4` = "36 to 40 years",
                              `5` = "41 to 45 years",
                              `6` = "46 to 50 years",
                              .ordered = TRUE),
         party_vote = recode_factor(party_vote,
                                    `1`= "CDU-CSU",
                                    `2`= "SPD",
                                    `3` = "FDP",
                                    `4` = "Gruene",
                                    `6` = "Linke",
                                    `42` = "AfD",
                                    `90` = "Other party",
                                    `91` = "Would not vote"),
         distrust_gov = inverter(trust_gov)) %>% 
  mutate(
    xenophobia = rowMeans(across(
      xeno1:xeno4))) %>% 
  mutate(across(contact1:contact4,
                ~recode(
                  .x,
                  `2` = 0))) %>% 
  mutate(contact = rowSums(across(
    contact1:contact4)))

1 The data

The data we use comes from the German General Social Survey - ALLBUS 2021.We have selected 20 variables of interest for our analysis. The dataset includes data for N = 5342 respondents.

1.1 Missing data

As not all of the respondents answered every question in the survey, we have missing data. Before we further explore the data, we want to know whether there are identifiable patterns of missingness in them.

library(visdat)

vis_miss(allbus_2021_subset)

3.2 Regression analysis

We use a logistic regression model to explore how trust in people is predicted by life satisfaction, mean xenophobic attitudes and the contact with foreigners.

allbus_2021_subset <- allbus_2021_subset %>% 
  mutate(distrust_gov_dic = ifelse(distrust_gov > 4, 0, 1))

library(broom)

model <- glm(distrust_gov_dic ~ 1 + life_satf + contact + xenophobia,
             family = binomial(link = "logit"),
             data = allbus_2021_subset)

tidy_model <- model %>% 
  tidy()

tidy_model %>% 
  knitr::kable()
term estimate std.error statistic p.value
(Intercept) 0.5337357 0.3051168 1.749283 0.0802420

xenophobia -0.3842072 0.0452828 -8.484614 0.0000000 
glance(model)
